I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve the API data using the default parameters:

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Now I'll use the data_processing_parser tool to parse the fetched API response into a structured format:

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll use the data_processing_validator to validate the parsed data structure. Since we don't have a specific schema, I'll use a generic validation approach:

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "data": {"type": "object"},
      "metadata": {"type": "object"}
    },
    "required": ["data", "metadata"]
  },
  "data": {
    "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
    "options": {}
  },
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            I'll use the network_poster tool to send the processed data to the destination API:

<tool_call>network_poster
{
  "destination": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "data": {
    "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
    "options": {}
  },
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            I'll check the dependencies for network_poster and execute the required integration_authenticator first:

<tool_call>integration_authenticator
{
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Now I'll retry the network_poster with authentication included in the options:

<tool_call>network_poster
{
  "destination": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "data": {
    "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
    "options": {}
  },
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {
    "auth": {
      "token": "token_493175",
      "type": "Bearer"
    }
  }
}
</tool_call>
